# Document Failure Map of Healthcare
EHR Document Readiness Project

Core Thesis
-----------
"Intake accepts documents. Discharge tests them."

Healthcare institutions typically collect legal authority documents administratively during intake.
However, the validity and operational usability of those documents are often only discovered later
during treatment decisions or discharge coordination.

This creates a structural failure gap in the system.


====================================================
LAYER 1 — HEALTHCARE PROCESS FLOW
====================================================

Family Preparation
        ↓
Facility Intake
        ↓
Administrative Document Capture
        ↓
Treatment Decision Point
        ↓
Discharge Coordination
        ↓
Post-Care Placement / Facility Transfer


====================================================
LAYER 2 — ESCALATION TIMELINE (T0–T8)
====================================================

T0  Assumed Readiness
    Family believes documents exist and are valid.

T1  Intake Collection
    Facility requests and receives documents.

T2  Administrative Capture
    Documents scanned or stored in records.

T3  Authority Assumed Valid
    Staff assumes documents will work if needed.

T4  Authority Required
    Treatment decision requires legal authority.

T5  Authority Questioned
    Staff begins questioning authority validity.

T6  Discharge Coordination
    Legal authority required for placement or transfer.

T7  Authority Conflict
    Family members or institutions dispute authority.

T8  Legal Escalation
    Guardianship proceedings or legal intervention.


====================================================
LAYER 3 — FAILURE CAUSE FRAMEWORK (F1–F7)
====================================================

F1  Missing Document
    Required authority document does not exist.

F2  Wrong Authority Type
    Medical vs financial authority mismatch.

F3  Expired or Outdated Document
    Document no longer legally valid.

F4  Document Inaccessible
    Original cannot be located or produced.

F5  Conflicting Authority
    Multiple individuals claim decision authority.

F6  Jurisdiction Mismatch
    Document not valid across state or institutional rules.

F7  Institutional Rejection
    Hospital or facility refuses to accept document.


====================================================
LAYER 4 — OPERATIONAL CONSEQUENCES (C1–C5)
====================================================

C1  Communication Blocked
    Staff cannot legally speak with family member.

C2  Consent Delay
    Treatment or medical decisions delayed.

C3  Discharge Delay
    Patient cannot be transferred or released.

C4  Family Conflict
    Disputes escalate between relatives.

C5  Legal Escalation
    Court or guardianship intervention required.


====================================================
ANALYTICAL MODEL
====================================================

Each documented case in the dataset is classified using three dimensions:

T-stage  → When the failure became visible
F-type   → Why the document failed
C-outcome → What operational damage occurred


Example Case Classification
---------------------------

Case #014

T6  Discharge Coordination
F4  Document Inaccessible
C3  Discharge Delay


Interpretation
--------------
The document failure was discovered during discharge planning because
the required document could not be produced, resulting in discharge delay.


====================================================
PROJECT PURPOSE
====================================================

The EHR Document Readiness dataset aims to measure:

1. How often authority documents fail during care transitions
2. What mechanisms cause the failures
3. What operational damage those failures create

Initial dataset target:
200 documented public cases (Reddit, caregiver forums, public discussions).

The dataset will allow analysis of:

• where failures are discovered
• what causes them
• how severe the operational impact becomes
